Four members of Kemerovo group arrested in Estonia and Spain
According to Postimees, the police in Spain detained the leader of the so-called Kemerovo group operating in the Estonian underworld, Slava Gulevich, known in the criminal world as Slava Kemerovski.
Gulevich, who was arrested in Spain, was arrested with the court’s permission.
Yesterday, the court also arrested three suspects detained in Estonia.
The suspects are members of the so-called Kemerovo criminal organisation, aged between 27 and 57, who are mainly involved in drug-related crimes.
The alleged leader of a criminal organisation was detained in Mijas, in the Spanish province of Malaga.
Three men were detained in Estonia as suspects, one of whom is, according to the data collected, a leading figure of a criminal organisation and two are members of a criminal organisation.
The data collected suggests that the tasks and roles in the criminal organisation were clearly allocated.
The aim of the activities of the criminal organisation was to commit drug offences and thereby earn criminal income," said Vahur Verte, the head of the pre-trial procedure in the criminal case.
"We do not rule out an increase in the number of suspects in this criminal case," the prosecutor added.
These are people who have been in the interest of law enforcement in the past, and some of them have served sentences for drug offences.
Mr Verte stressed that cooperation with his Spanish colleagues had been important throughout the investigation.
“International co-operation has become commonplace for us, and this week’s operation demonstrates the success of the co-operation,” prosecutor Verte said.
The head of the Central Criminal Police, Ago Leis, said the detentions were preceded by a preliminary investigation that lasted for nearly a year and a half.
"In the first half of the week, the long-term work was realised and we simultaneously detained suspects of crimes in Estonia and Spain," he said.
Leis added that Central Criminal Police officers were instrumental in detaining him in Spain.
For years now, we have had good contact and understanding with the Spanish police and the Civil Guard.
These detentions are yet another message to the criminals that we can catch them from the other side of Europe," Leis said.
The information gathered so far clearly indicates that the men who were suspected may continue to commit new crimes while still at large, which is why the prosecutor’s office requested their arrest and the court approved it.
The man arrested in Spain is awaiting his extradition to Estonia.
Real estate, vehicles and cash have been seized to secure the confiscation in this case.
Pre-trial proceedings in criminal cases are conducted by the Central Criminal Police’s Organised Crime Bureau and headed by the Public Prosecutor’s Office.
In 2005, the Tallinn City Court convicted Slava Gulevich of extortion and sentenced him to five years in prison.
In the middle of the last decade, Gulevich was considered the second most important man in the Estonian criminal world after the then underworld leader Nikolai Tarankov.
Gulevich, who came from Kemerovo, rose to prominence in the Estonian underworld in the early 1990s when he began to deal with blackmail in Tallinn.
He allegedly taxed taxi drivers and prostitutes at various hotels and demanded a monthly roofing fee from businessmen.
International joint operations, confiscations of proceeds of crime and court judgments in force confirm that the fight against organised crime is effective.
For example, the latest court judgments, the eight defendants separated from the so-called Dikayev criminal case, who were confiscated EUR 80 000 in criminal proceeds, or the court judgment against nine persons for Igor Aleynikov's creation in 2006 of a criminal association aimed at the illegal trade in contraband cigarettes and the commission of crimes related to human trafficking in Ida-Viru County and Southern Estonia.
The amount of confiscated proceeds is approximately 71,500 euros.
Success in these cases has been ensured by the fact that police officers exchange information and evidence with foreign colleagues on a daily basis and, if necessary, take action together in any country of the European Union.
Civil Rights Group Warns of Traveling to Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has warned black people traveling to Missouri against discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group said in a statement: “The NAACP Travel Notice for Missouri, effective until August 28, 2017, calls on all African-American travelers, visitors, and Missourians to be particularly alert and extremely cautious when traveling throughout the state, given the range of suspicious racial events that have occurred throughout the state.”
According to the NAACP, the group was prompted to issue a travel warning by a recent Missouri law, which makes it harder to win cases of discrimination, as well as the fact that the state’s law enforcement officers are disproportionately targeting minorities.
“People’s civil rights are being violated.
They are pulled to the side of the road because of their skin color, they are beaten or killed,” Rod Chapel, president of the NAACP Missouri branch, told The Kansas City Star newspaper.
“We’ve never had so many complaints before.”
This is the first such warning the organization has issued against a U.S. state.
The group referred to such events as racist insults against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of 28-year-old black Tory Sanders from Tennessee.
Sanders died in suspicious circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas while driving through the state and was arrested by Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
In addition, the note refers to a recent report by the Missouri Attorney General, which shows that black drivers in the state are 75% more likely to be stopped than white drivers.
“Notes are meant to make people aware and alert their families, friends, and coworkers about what might be happening in Missouri,” Chapel said.
“People need to be prepared, whether it’s taking bail money or telling relatives they’re going through the state.”
Based on the latest data from the FBI's hate crime reporting program, 100 hate crimes were documented in Missouri in 2015, placing the state at number 16 in the cross-section of the state in terms of similar violations.
The travel alert is also a response to Missouri’s new law, which makes it harder for a company to sue for discrimination in the search for housing or work.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had previously issued travel notes for Texas and Arizona after those states passed immigration laws obliging local authorities to arrest people for immigration violations because, according to the ACLU, this increases racial profiling.
Usually, the State Department issues travel warnings about other countries, but recently, interest groups have begun to use this measure in response to certain domestic laws and trends.
Hepatitis: what could everyone know about the different forms of this serious disease?
Hepatitis, or inflammation of the liver, can be caused by five different types of hepatitis A, B, C, D and E viruses.
All these viruses cause acute inflammation of the liver tissue.
However, chronic hepatitis B and C can develop into liver cirrhosis, or liver wrinkling, and liver cancer.
The epidemiology adviser of the Health Board, Kuulo Kutsar, says that the symptoms of acute hepatitis are the same for all types of liver inflammation – fever, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, greyish stools, dark urine, muscle and joint pain, and yellowing of the skin and mucous membranes.
The last symptom of the disease also comes from the popular name of hepatitis jaundice.
In children, hepatitis can pass without signs of the disease.
Different types of hepatitis can be determined only on the basis of data from a laboratory study.
Acute hepatitis can transform into chronic hepatitis and progress for decades without symptoms, which means that a person may not know anything about his dangerous liver-damaging disease.
Kuulo Kutsar brings out the different forms of hepatitis and describes their course in more detail.
Hepatitis viruses spread from a sick person and infect us by eating contaminated food or drinking water, by having sex, by dropping the infected person’s stools on hands and from hands to food, surfaces, objects, getting into the mouth, and by using drugs.
The risk group of hepatitis A infection includes family members and caregivers of the affected person, people with chronic liver disease, people who have sex with an infected person, men who have sex with men, drug addicts, and travelers visiting countries with high prevalence of hepatitis A.
The infection can be prevented by vaccination, in particular, vaccination is recommended for people who travel a lot and are at risk for hepatitis A.
In addition, it is important to meet daily hygiene requirements: wash or disinfect hands, wash all fruits and vegetables before eating.
Hepatitis B viruses are spread through contact with the blood of a sick person, injection of drugs, tattooing, piercing, use of blood-contaminated household products (tooth brushes, shaving devices), sex with a donor blood, a person who is suspected of having hepatitis, and from the mother to the fetus/newborn child who is ill with hepatitis.
The risk group for hepatitis B infection includes injecting drug users, sexual partners of the infected person, men who have sex with men, newborn babies of the infected mother, sick family members and caregivers, health care workers, rescue workers and police officers exposed to blood and other bodily fluids, and travellers visiting countries with high levels of hepatitis B disease.
In order to prevent hepatitis B, it is possible to vaccinate people; in particular, it is recommended to vaccinate people at risk, as well as people with chronic liver diseases, HIV infection, sexually transmitted diseases and diabetes.
Other preventive measures against hepatitis B include: refraining from using foreign hygiene and manicure equipment, other sharps and needles, tattooing and piercing, and using condoms for sex that is potentially infectious, or avoiding risky sexual behaviour.
Vaccination against hepatitis B is part of the national immunization program in Estonia and is free of charge for children.
Hepatitis C viruses are spread through contact with the blood of a sick person, injection of drugs, tattooing, piercing, use of blood-contaminated household fluids, sex with a donor, hepatitis suspect person, and from the mother to the fetus/newborn child.
The risk group for hepatitis C infection includes injecting drug users, sexual partners of the infected person, men who have sex with men, newborn babies of the infected mother, sick family members and caregivers, health care workers, rescue workers and police officers exposed to blood and other bodily fluids, persons with HIV infection, and travellers visiting countries with high levels of hepatitis C disease.
Hepatitis C prevention measures include: Avoiding the use of foreign hygiene and manicure products, other sharps and needles, tattooing and piercing, and using condoms in case of unsafe sex.
There is no vaccine against hepatitis C.
Hepatitis D is caused by the hepatitis D virus, which multiplies in the presence of the hepatitis B virus.
Therefore, hepatitis D infection occurs with hepatitis B or as a superinfection in patients with chronic hepatitis B.
Hepatitis D viruses are spread by contact with blood and other body fluids, contaminated syringes and needles, by sexual contact, and rarely by infection from the mother to the fetus.
The risk group of hepatitis D is chronic carriers of hepatitis B virus and people who do not have immunity to hepatitis B.
An effective preventive measure is vaccination with a hepatitis B vaccine, which also protects a person from infection with the hepatitis D virus.
Hepatitis E viruses are spread by faecal-oral route through drinking water and food, including eating low-heat-treated beef, fish and shellfish, with donor blood, with shared syringes, and from an infected mother to the fetus.
Travelers can become infected with hepatitis E in countries with high rates of the disease.
Prevention measures for hepatitis E include compliance with hygiene requirements: wash or disinfect hands after going to the toilet, before cooking and eating, after caring for the sick.
Wash fruits and vegetables before consumption, avoid eating little heat-treated beef, fish and seafood, drink only safe drinking water, and refrain from using drugs.
