Blocking critics from Facebook don’t run for state office if you can’t stand criticism from voters
The father of our country knew a lot about unfavorable media coverage.
The American people loved George Washington, but it didn’t take long for the newspapers to beat him up about everything from domestic politics to his policies.
Criticism, of course, irritated him.
But he did not force his critics to remain silent.
For in 1783 Washington said that "freedom of speech may be taken away from us, and silently and silently we may be led, like sheep, to slaughter."
Which brings me to Larry Hogan, the governor of Maryland, who has to work hard to be more like Washington.
Hogan’s employees have blocked and deleted at least 450 people who posted their opinions on his official Facebook page.
Earlier this week, he was sued by the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU).
The case was dismissed by the governor’s office, and online commentaries were teeming with reactions in the form of “Who cares?”
"It's just Facebook," many said.
But it does matter.
And it matters a lot when it comes to a man like Hogan.
He's an amazingly popular Republican governor in an overwhelmingly democratic state.
His approval percentage is the second best among the 50 governors in the country.
Hogan is not an unthinking reactionary whimper.
He has led the state with a firm hand and has stood firm in his principles.
In addition, he has been quite adept at using Facebook as the main tool for communicating with his voters, for example, presenting his bald head cheerfully for the first time since chemotherapy.
Thus, the governor’s page, which is an officially-marked public forum run by taxpayers’ dollar-paying staff, blocking people from visiting is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
Hogan’s spokesman, Amelia Chasse, defended the governor’s behavior in an interview with The Washington Post, arguing that blocking comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it’s too easy to paint a picture of online trolls, spammers, or angry people.
The Post spoke to several real people that Hogan had blocked.
And that's exactly what they are, real people who interact with their chosen leaders -- teachers, business owners, and pastors, not internet trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and by no means obscene.
The pastor quoted the Bible in his post, emphasizing Hogan’s Catholicism.
Lakshmi Sarma Raman, a lawyer from Bowie, Maryland, did not incite hatred, but real hate crimes.
“I politely commented that I was disappointed that he had not responded to hate crimes or other recent news,” she wrote in the Post’s comment section.
“I also don’t like the idea that when a large number of people comment on the same topic, someone will immediately indifferently call it a collective effort instead of acknowledging that it’s a large number of concerned citizens.”
What the governor’s office called a “directed spam attack,” others would probably call “public support.”
The Facebook era allows you to easily match messages by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It’s much cleaner than it used to be, when you had to send out workers to do the same thing, so that they would gather up the newspapers with critical editorials and burn them, or arrest the protesters and force them to remain silent.
But that’s exactly what’s happening now, just digitally.
Hogan isn’t the first government official to be criticized for toothing Facebook and other social media.
President Trump has been sued by Twitter users who have been blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first landmark judgments on this subject was made last week in Virginia.
U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria ruled that the chairwoman of Loudoun County Oversight Board violated the First Amendment when she blocked a voter from her Facebook page.
In Kentucky, the ACLU also visited Governor Matt Bevin (R) for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington, D.C., affordable postage had a similar effect to the Internet.
Between 1776 and 1800, the number of newspapers quadrupled, and anonymous writers pounded his style of management.
And even then, Washington had to deal with anonymous trolls.
People wrote letters to newspapers under pseudonyms such as Juricola, Valerius, Belisarius, and Portius, razing Washington to the ground.
According to historical documents gathered by George Washington’s online letter collection project, his office was buried under petitions criticizing his views on the friendship, trade and shipping agreements with Britain.
But he did not force them to remain silent.
Freedom of expression, dissent and debate are the foundations of our country.
And right leadership means accepting it.
