Poverty and Death in Indonesia's Rich Land
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn't use the stove.
He rarely even uses a potty.
In a wooden cottage in Enarotal, the capital of the reluctant Paniai regency in Papua, Indonesia, a housewife places a sweet potato called nota, in the local language, right on the fire.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed from the fire and eagerly eaten with unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the mud floor with no furniture and does her daily chores, such as washing laundry with turbid water from a nearby swamp.
A bucket in an unroofed room plays the role of a toilet.
Since she is the youngest of her husband’s four wives, she is not assigned to any field.
Polygamy is common here.
Working late can be dangerous, however, as most of the men in the village are unemployed and many of them drink heavily, and there are also soldiers here.
"No one dares to go around the village after five o'clock in the evening," he says.
This is a rare glimpse of life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was incorporated into Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum in which only 1,026 elderly people were forced to vote in front of the occupiers.
The movement, which encouraged the liberation of the Dutch from domination, quickly turned its rage against the government of Jakarta, which continues to keep the region under its strong control, keeping away from foreign journalists and human rights watchdogs.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, leaving the eastern part of the island to independent Papua New Guinea.
Enarotal is both a remote and abandoned place. To get here, you have to fly 90 minutes from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and then take a five-hour journey that will make you sick with a rental car.
There is no public transport.
With a population of about 19,000, the city consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fencing and covered with wavy iron roofs, whose rust has turned various shades of yellowish-brown.
Very few Indonesians have made the journey here, let alone journalists, and hardly any foreigners have been here either.
Before the arrival of the Christian missionaries, the Papuans of Mee Pago worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes as well.
“We weren’t used to wearing such clothes,” Degei says, referring to his colorful hand-woven turban, dark blouse, and bright skirt.
"Before that, we used to wear only leaves on our bodies."
Papua is the poorest province in Indonesia, with 28% of people living below the poverty line, and infant mortality and illiteracy statistics are among the worst in Asia.
But it is also Indonesia’s golden land.
Just 100 km from Pania, a mountainous province of about 153,000 people in New Jersey, lies the world’s largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based company Freeport McMoran.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined about $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua can boast of consumable wood reserves estimated at USD 78 billion.
But these riches are the source of Papuan suffering, as they result in the suffocating presence of a powerful Indonesian army.
A 2005 study by The New York Times found that Freeport paid local military personnel and units about $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 per officer.
This golden goose is threatened by the Papuans’ efforts to secure greater autonomy, and they are mercilessly treated.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military.
According to the Asian Human Rights Commission, the mass killings in the highlands of the Papuan tribes in the 1970s were the equivalent of genocide.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the area.
The 2016 report by the Archbishopric of Birsbane, “We Will Lose Everything,” contains testimonies of atrocities committed in the previous year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture (according to another report, rape and electric shocks are particularly prevalent) and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
“It’s hard to count the number of victims because these kinds of incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The screws have been tightened even more, as Papua’s natural resources have led to an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
83% of the province’s 3.5 million inhabitants are Christian, but the demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from Indonesia’s crowded islands of Java, Kalimantan, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese family canteens sell gado-gado with crispy chicken and mixed vegetables, served with peanut sauce.
The locals can't compete with them.
“Migrants began selling chicken and vegetables on the traditional market at lower prices than local beans,” explains 24-year-old Abeth You, born in Paniai, who moved to the provincial capital Jayapura for work.
"The native Papuan mama-mama [women] are therefore losing market share."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, who is popularly known as Jokowi, vowed to address these inequalities and human rights violations in Papua in his 2014 election campaign.
The former carpenter won 27 of the 29 constituencies, including Paniai, on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But very little has changed in Papua and the locals feel betrayed.
“Our hearts are broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokow in the expectation that he would live up to our hopes of restoring justice,” You says.
In fact, just two months after Jokowi took office in October, Paniai was in a slump.
On December 7, 2014, 11 children were singing Christmas carols on a fire in Enarotal when two Indonesian soldiers appeared on a motorcycle in the darkness.
Shocked children told them they should turn on the headlights.
According to local pastor Yavedt Tebai, one of the soldiers was offended by their tone of voice and later returned with four soldiers.
According to victims and witnesses, drunken soldiers chased children and beat them with the handles of their rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at the children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was so badly beaten that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby Electoral Commission building was set on fire, and the next day things escalated even further.
About 1,000 young Papuan men, women, and children rallied for justice on a football field in front of the local police station and military command center.
They wore ceremonial hunting bows and performed the Waita dance of the Papuan honey pago tribe, during which they ran around and imitated birdsong.
Some protesters began throwing stones at police and military personnel.
"If the crowd resists more than three times, shoot them," according to an official document seen by TIME magazine, but not issued to local media outlets.
Yeremias Kayame (56), the elder of the district of Kego Koto in Enarotal, sensed the threat and called for peace, asking the crowd to go home.
No one wanted to listen.
"When I turned around, I was shot in the left wrist," he told TIME magazine in his brightly colored treehouse porch.
Kayame still doesn't know who the shooter was, but says the bullet came from the ranks of the assembled soldiers.
"There were a lot of people, there were a lot of shots," he added.
Alfius Youw, a local man, was shot three times, according to a cousin who witnessed the shooting.
“I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him,” Yohanes, who like many Indonesians, uses only one name, told TIME magazine.
"I saw that he was dead... I kissed him."
Yotje Mende, Chief Inspector of the Papuan Police Force, told reporters that his officers only guaranteed the security of their department, as it was under attack.
“We must defend ourselves if we are threatened with death,” said Pudjo Sulistiyo, a Papuan police spokesman.
"It's a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many injured.
The news of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the following day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing his condolences to the families of the victims and promising to address the abuses that have taken place in Papua.
"I want to solve this case now so that it will never happen again in the future," he said.
In October 2016, Security Minister Wiranto announced that he would establish an extrajudicial mechanism to resolve crimes against human rights.
Almost immediately, however, the excuses followed.
Most of the crimes happened a long time ago.
Some of these occurred in the 1990s and early 2000s.
“We are committed to solving these crimes, but we have to follow certain processes,” he said.
Speaking to TIME magazine in Jakarta on 5 June, however, Wiranto retracted his comments, saying that he had no intention of setting up a mechanism to deal with complaints in Papua.
Instead, he said, “everything will be settled according to the law.”
Wiranto, who has been accused by the United Nations of human rights crimes over the deaths of more than 1,000 people in Timor-Leste during the bloody 1999 independence referendum, said that 11 human rights crimes had already been solved in Papua, including those in Pania.
The families of the victims of Paniai accepted such claims with grim disbelief.
“I’ve been interrogated four times in the last three years, but no progress has been made,” Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
He says he still lives in fear years later.
"I'm scared," he says.
"I'm afraid the military will arrest me, I'm afraid I'll be shot."
His brother Yacobus confirmed that the people of Paniai were afraid to dissect the incident.
He said he was beaten by the military after helping bury four victims.
"After the bodies were buried, the army came looking for me," he says.
The shootings have not stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police shot villagers in the neighboring Deiyai province.
One person was killed and 17 injured, including children, when a row broke out between villagers and the construction company manager, who refused to transport the unconscious man to the hospital.
This man, 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died en route to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested in front of the company’s office at the construction site.
Police said villagers threw stones at police officers, who responded with warning shots.
But according to locals, a mobile brigade (Indonesian military police) began shooting at a crowd, killing one person.
"We were in a big panic, we're afraid of revenge," 29-year-old Domingo Badii, who lives near the hospital, told TIME magazine.
"I've been hiding in my house for two days."
The Deiyai Parliament has called for the prosecution of the police officers involved and for the withdrawal of a mobile police brigade from the region.
Paniai has always been a problem for the Indonesian Government.
The lack of meaningful development is fuelling the discontent of the honey, Moni, Dani, and Damal tribes living in the verdant highlands of Papua.
Many of them have joined the Free Papua Movement's (VPL) rebel army, which says it defends the rights of the Papuans by occasionally carrying out attacks and kidnappings among Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the leaders of the VPL are from Pania, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In response, under the pretext of "defending state sovereignty", the military has arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of people in Paniais in recent years.
Some of them will never show up again.
Among the people of Papua, Paniad is known as the "tragic forgotten place".
Poverty breeds discontent.
The little rice that is sold in Enarotal is too expensive for locals to buy.
Bread is just as inaccessible.
People grow all their food themselves mainly sweet potatoes, in addition to a little fruit and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the work of women, each of whom is able to care for four or five sweet potato fields.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, the rest is sold on the local market.
Ten sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequality has deepened between indigenous Papuans and new migrants, who have been arriving in abundance since the opening of new routes to Nabire Airport.
The few jobs that exist go to better educated and wealthier migrants.
Papuans themselves often lack the capital or skills to run a competitive business.
“Young people are not interested in staying here because there are no jobs and no money,” says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai tribal council.
Isolation keeps the eyes of the world away from Papua.
There are also severe restrictions on foreign media.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were expelled from Papua because "they did not observe the relevant practices", although they had been given a rare permission to film.
Phelim Kine, deputy head of Human Rights Watch’s Asia department, said Jokow’s election pledges to lift restrictions on reporting to promote transparency and development had not been implemented.
"Journalists trying to report from Papua's most troubled eastern provinces and West Papua in Indonesia face new threats of visa rejection and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
The lack of press scrutiny means that international pressure on the Indonesian Government is largely limited to Papua's immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific nations—Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands, and Solomon Islands—stimulated the UN Human Rights Council to investigate “various widespread crimes” in Papua, including the shooting of Paniai.
These same countries have historically supported the VPL.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir dismissed the group's accusations, telling reporters in Jakarta that "democracy and freedom of the press remain in place in Indonesia, making it difficult to bury evidence of human rights violations."
The local people want more attention from foreign governments.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by the country's human rights envoy Kees Van Bar, visited Jayapura on 4 May, the local people broke their silence, according to a source who was present at the meeting but who wished to remain anonymous, urging them: "We want freedom."
Indonesia will hold another presidential election in 2019, but Papuans do not believe they will vote for Jokow again.
"Jokowi is a man of good intentions, but he is surrounded by people involved in the shooting of Paniai," said Hobai, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokow to understand that not only are the people of Paniai constantly living under the threat of the predatory army, but they are also suffering from poor education and health services.
According to Gobai, the people of Paniai, like other Papuans, regard their vote for Jokow as a debt to be repaid.
"They don't need money, they want justice," he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the shooting victims of Paniai managed to carry out yet another symbolic insurrection by burying the body of one of the victims on the ground opposite the police station and military base.
Knowing that justice may never be done, they will not let those responsible forget their crimes.
"One of our family members was killed," Yacobus says with his head lowered.
"What else can we do?"
