The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has reversed its decision to delay the Obama-era regulation that requires states to limit emissions of smog, one day after 15 states sued the agency over the move.
The EPA announced its decision to proceed with “Ozone Assessment Procedures 2015” late Wednesday, saying it showed the agency’s commitment to working with states.
“We believe we need to engage in dialogue with and listen to our state partners,” said Scott Pruitt, the EPA’s chief executive.
Pruitt had announced in June the EPA’s intention to delay the ozone measurements, which measure smog pollution in different parts of the country, to determine where its level should be reduced by one year until October 2018 in order to meet the stricter air quality standard.
The 15 predominantly Democratic states filed a lawsuit with the District of Columbia on Tuesday, saying the ruling was illegal.
President Donald Trump’s administration has tried to pull back on a number of environmental regulations imposed by former President Barack Obama. According to Trump, this is part of a broader plan to boost economic growth.
But these efforts have sparked backlash among Democrats and conservation groups who are concerned about the impact of increased pollution on human health.
The EPA’s website states that breathing ozone-containing air “could reduce the working capacity of the lungs and increase the risk of respiratory diseases,” such as asthma.
