New results of age assessment tests for Swedish asylum seekers published
The latest results show that more than 80 percent of those tested were estimated to be older than 18, but not all believe in the accuracy of the results.
The Swedish National Institute of Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing earlier this year.
The tests were created to provide a more accurate age assessment during the asylum application process after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticised for failing to correctly determine the age of a number of refugees who allegedly were minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases for testing and the Forensic Institute has issued a total of 2,481 test results between mid-March and 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were rated as 18 years or older, and an additional 25 cases were rated by the Forensic Institute that the test subject “could be 18 years or older.”
In 432 cases, it was concluded that a person is "probably younger than 18".
Tests are only used when a person’s age is in question.
According to Johan G<0xC3><0xB6>ransson, who works at the Institute of Forensic Medicine, the results are consistent compared to previous months.
"We don't see much of a difference compared to the statistics from previous months, the numbers are quite consistent," he told The Local newspaper.
The fact that the majority of cases were estimated to be older than 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers have lied about their age.
The institute issued the results of 581 tests in May, and said in 442 cases, “there are indications that the person being tested is 18 years of age or older.”
But when the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet looked at the results of these 581 tests, it turned out that in 243 cases, the person had directly stated that he would be 18 this year.
This medical age estimation method, which involves X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI of knee joints, after which they are allowed to be analyzed by dentists and radiologists, has been criticized in some circles.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at the Karolinska Institutet, whose job includes assessing people’s biological maturity to find out if they went through puberty earlier or later than usual.
“I’ve had reason to think about it and I don’t think the measurement method we’re using now should be used.
Determining the biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't say for sure, then we shouldn't pretend we can," he told Metro.
But Johan G<0xC3><0xB6>ransson of the Institute of Forensic Medicine defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, it can be said that the risk of classifying a child inaccurately into an adult is low.
The highest risk, around 10%, is when the person is just under 18."
