The electric car revolution will significantly change the demand for metals.
Who are the winners and losers?
Not only will the electric car revolution fundamentally change everything from the fuel market to the infrastructure, it will also create new winners and losers in the metal market.
While mining giants like Glencore can say that from one place they win and from another they lose, smaller mining companies are not helped.
Glencore currently earns from coal and oil, but demand for cobalt, lithium, copper, aluminum and nickel will continue to grow in the era of electric cars.
This year, the expansion of electric vehicles has been boosted by the decisions of the governments of the United Kingdom, France and Norway, which promise to ban the sale of new cars using fossil fuels in the coming decades.
As a result, Volvo has already announced its plans to phase out the internal combustion engine, and Tesla will launch a cheaper Model 3 electric car.
According to Bloomberg New Energy Finance, more electric cars will be sold than cars powered by oil over the next two decades.
"For some metals, it changes everything," Simona Gambranini, a commodity analyst at Capital Economics, told Bloomberg.
We have already seen a great impact on metals such as cobalt and lithium, for which demand has been growing for years.
Electric cars have about three times as much copper as conventional cars, Glencore said.
Even more copper is needed at charging stations, which is why Exane BNP Paribas estimates that it will increase copper demand by about five percent by 2025.
The growth in demand for electric car batteries means additional demand for lithium, cobalt, graphite and manganese.
Glencore’s growing electric car trend will benefit from rising copper prices and being the world’s largest producer of cobalt, the Jefferies Group predicted.
The other winners of the electric car race are Freeport-McMoRan and First Quantum Minerals.
The market is already responding to a changing trend.
This year, the London Metal Exchange has seen a 70 percent increase in the price of cobalt.
The price increase last year was 37 percent.
The price of copper has also risen by 14% this year, mainly due to economic growth.
Glencore’s stock rose 20 percent in London, surpassing rivals Rio Tinto Group, BHP Billiton and Anglo American.
On the losing side are lead companies such as Recyclex and Campine, which have to adapt to the new era.
The main end-uses of lead are batteries that supply current to the starters of petrol and diesel cars.
Electric cars use lithium-ion batteries.
"This is a serious risk to lead demand unless it is found to have another purpose to overcome the drop in demand," said Michael Widmer, head of metal market analysis at Bank of America Merrill Lynch.
The effect of the unwinding trend in the form of lead price movement has not yet been noticed.
Lead has risen 17 percent this year, making it the best metal among London’s major industrial metals.
Investors will see problems with metal only in the distant future.
"I'm not sure it's that bad for lead, because cheap oil keeps conventional cars in competition," said Herwig Schmidt, sales manager at metal broker Triland Metals.
When the demand for lead falls, it happens slowly.
This may happen in about 10 years.
In the meantime, stricter emission standards mean that demand for hybrid cars will increase, which will depend on lead-based batteries developed in frequent engine launches, the international lead and zinc research organization estimates.
Light metals such as aluminum replace steel, as a lighter car can travel further with less electricity.
This explains the additional demand of 1,6 million tonnes of aluminium between 2013 and 2016.
This accounts for 2.7% of the world’s aluminium production.
This trend is likely to worsen, Widmer said.
The price of aluminium has risen by 13 percent this year, as the growing demand from car manufacturers has led to a market deficit.
Steel producers don't sleep.
AK Steel Holding is partnering with General Motors to use nanotechnology to produce lightweight car bodies.
ArcelorMittal and Tata Steel Europe are also trying to develop a lighter alloy steel to resist aluminum plating.
"High-strength steel should be the answer to this development," said Sylvain Brunet, an analyst at Exane BNP Paribas.
We have seen some progress in Europe.
The end of the oil age can also bring suffering to platinum.
Last year, about half of that precious metal was used as catalysts for diesel-powered cars, metal refiner Johnson Matthey said.
“Many raw materials that are in high demand now, such as oil and platinum, may not be in high demand in the future,” said Bernard Dahdah, raw material analyst at Natixis.
This does not mean that raw materials as a whole will become less important, but their importance will change within 15 years.
Platinum manufacturers believe there will be continued demand for diesel hybrid cars.
Marc Grynberg, CEO of Uncore, said that there will continue to be more hybrid cars sold than fully electric cars in 2025.
The big hope for platinum manufacturers in the 10 year perspective is the hydrogen cell-based cars developed by Toyota Motor and Hyundai Motos, which rely on platinum to produce electricity from hydrogen.
