The FFP was founded by Michel Platini after he was elected president of UEFA in 2007.
This former French player believed that clubs that fall into large debts in search of success were in fact engaged in cheating and risked ruin if banks or owners were to give up support.
Since 2011, FFP has focused on monitoring the losses of the clubs instead of their debts.
This change means that the business model that Roman Abramovich first used in 2003 at Chelsea – buying a club with potential and then making big money to improve the team and build a global brand – will be more difficult to implement.
During the current three-year assessment period, which runs until 2018, FFP clubs may incur losses of up to EUR 30 million.
And despite Platini’s shameless rejection of the presidency in 2015, his UEFA successor, Aleksander Ceferin, remains committed to preventing overspending.
"The FFP is certainly not dead and we will certainly continue to strengthen these rules in the future," Andrea Traverso, who oversees the FFP at UEFA, told The Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid Neymar for the sale-and-lease-back clause in the form of a single payment, it is possible for them to split this amount for accounting purposes throughout the duration of the contract.
Neymar entered into a five-year contract, so it is possible to indicate a transitional fee of EUR 44,4 million per year for the next five years.
In the first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014, PSG, together with Abu Dhabi-owned Manchester City, received the most severe penalties.
PSG was fined €60 million ($82 million at the time), later reduced to €20 million, and was required to restrict the Champions League team to 21 players instead of the usual 25 for the 2014–15 season.
UEFA is looking for clubs that might try to outsmart the regulatory financial institutions by blowing up their incomes through companies affiliated with the club’s owners.
A Qatari company may sponsor PSG, but if the value of the sponsorship is considered to be above standard market rates, UEFA would not allow it to count as official income.
This is what happened in 2014 when UEFA decided that the value of support from the Qatar Tourism Authority PSG was inflated.
