The secret of clean beaches: night cleaning and poor beach weather
Colder summer weather also means a smaller cleaning effort on the beaches of Tallinn.
“When there is no weather, there are people on the beach, and when there is no weather, there are no people.”
Seagulls are howling on Stroomi Beach in northern Tallinn.
For them, the melodic competition comes from a low-speed rattling tractor that plows stripes onto the patch.
In fact, the latter sifts through the sand at a depth of three inches [7 cm], picking up marine debris and human debris —bottle caps, cigarette butts, and so forth.
People still come to the beach, whether the water is warm or not.
When the weather is nice, there are people on the beach, and when there are no people, there are also no people," says Aleksandr Usov, head of beach cleaning at the Haabersti Haldus private limited company.
It’s 6:30 a.m. and there’s a hard cleaning going on on the beach, because at 8 p.m. the square has to be clean for people.
Usov's on duty at 4:00.
In addition to Stroomi, he also keeps an eye on Pirita, Lake Harku, Kakumäe and Paljasaare Pikakari beaches.
The amount of rubbish has decreased.
Years ago there was so much more.
People can now appreciate what is being done for them,” says Usov, who has been cleaning the beach for 15 years.
Before, when something new was put up, it was already broken the next day.
Now they're keeping what's on the beach.
The price of a clean beach
One of the biggest jobs on Estonian beaches is cleaning up the sea litter washed up on the shore.
For example, in Pirita beach, 400,000 tons of it has to be transported to the beach season.
"It's an incredible amount," Usov notes.
The second big category is household waste, that is, everything that people leave behind.
The one-and-a-half-mile stretch of Stroomi Beach has eight large garbage cans that need to be emptied three times a week.
There is so much rubbish.
However, the colder summer weather has meant that litter is one fifth less than otherwise.
The third category is abandoned property.
They're mostly children's toys.
This time Usov has scooped out a dozen model cars from the sand.
They are waiting for the owners on the wooden road to the beach.
Usov already knows that he will soon find them again in the sand.
Children come to the beach and take toys to drown them in the sand again.
Garbage to be scattered
Erika Scholler, the representative of Haaberst’s administrative services, admits that the screening work of the tractor is disrupted by locals.
Noise, which lasts from the hours of the night to the early morning, disturbs the sleep of people living in the neighbourhood.
This work is impossible during the day.
In one month, the beach has to be sifted twice.
“If we don’t, the district will fine us,” Scholler notes.
However, like Pirita, Pikakari and Pärnu, the goal is to get Stroomi beach under the international blue flag quality mark.
“Compared to Europe, there is much more work to be done in Estonia to maintain beaches,” says Scholler.
We have more seaweed and rocks, and it's harder to sift the sand.
There is less rubbish on our beaches than anywhere else in Europe.
When Martin, who lives near Stroomi Beach, hears about the rubbish on the beach, he enters the conversation circle of a journalist and cleaning staff, highlighting the current problems on the beach.
There's a disgusting picture everywhere in the morning.
The problem is with the birds and the bottle pickers who have pulled the garbage bags inside out,” Martin says.
Although it is difficult to assume that people will be able to change their current behavioural habits, Martin hopes that the city government will do something about the rubbish bins and put lids on them, for example, to prevent at least birds from visiting them.
In general, however, Martin is pleased with the development of Stroomi beach.
You can see the city is taking care of that.
With children's playgrounds, illuminated and freshly paved roads, it has become more pleasant.
Once upon a time, roller skates could only ride on one road,” notes Martin.
Treasure hunter's finds in Stroomi: coins, coins only
A 40-year-old Dimitri, who is scouring the beach with a metal detector as a treasure hunter, has taken advantage of the low tide period of the morning.
He does not believe that he will find anything valuable today or in the future.
The sea gods are not generous enough.
“I’ve been working on this for a year and haven’t found anything of value yet,” Dmitri says.
As a hobby treasure hunter, Dmitri’s treasure bag contains some euro coins, bottle caps and also dangerous nails, which later throws them in the trash.
There are usually coins.
"Gold, rings and the like usually don't exist," says the treasure hunter.
Bank of England keeps interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce that interest rates will remain at the same level, as weak economic growth and easing inflation have softened speculation about the rise.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will remain sluggish as tight household incomes have put interest rates on hold.
Policymakers at the Bank’s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) voted to keep the 6:2 rate at 0.25%, with fewer members calling for an increase this month as slow economic growth has weakened support for the rise.
In its quarterly inflation report, the bank cut its growth forecast for 2017 to 1.7% and for 2018 to 1.6%, warning that pressure on household incomes will continue as inflation is still expected to rise to close to 3% in the autumn.
At the same time, the bank also signaled that the growth of the rates will be necessary in the next few years to contain the inflation caused by Brexit and that higher than expected loan costs may be necessary in the financial markets.
Members also voted to partially withdraw the mammoth package that was launched a year ago as a result of Brexit.
The bank will end a time-limited funding scheme in February that will provide banks with cheap funding, although it said it now expects a <0xC2><0xA3>15bn increase in supply under the scheme, amounting to <0xC2><0xA3>115bn.
In the minutes of the decision on the rate, the bank says: "In the central forecast of the MPC, gross domestic product (GDP) will remain powerless in the near future, as the difficult situation of real household incomes will continue to have an impact on consumption."
In terms of rates, it was reiterated that a "some tightening of monetary policy" is needed to ease inflation, to a "slightly greater extent" than is expected in the markets.
The stock exchange is currently forecasting a first rise in the third quarter of next year and a second rise in 2020.
However, the bank stressed that any jumps are gradual and limited.
The bank’s reduced growth forecasts for this year and next year are comparable to those of May, 1.9% and 1.7%, respectively.
The forecast for growth of 1.8 per cent in 2018 remained unchanged.
After this news, the pound fell against the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell 0.5% to USD 1.31 and 0.4% to EUR 1.11.
The decision not to make any changes is due to recent disappointing growth figures, which have dampened growing expectations due to an increase in GDP in the second quarter, from 0.2% in the previous three months to 0.3%.
The bank says the growth is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it will pick up slightly by the end of the year.
The bank’s latest inflation report gave households suffering from rising inflation and miserable wage increases little reason to rejoice, saying that the situation will get a little worse before it improves.
It was added that monetary policy cannot prevent income shocks in the next few years, but towards the end of the three-year forecast, wages are expected to recover significantly.
Due to the weak pound, the economy is also stimulated by the growing demand for British production, which partially offsets lower costs for consumers.
The decision comes a year after the rates were moved to 0.25% last August after a shocking EU referendum that caused the pound to suddenly weaken.
According to the bank, it will probably take four years to fully breathe life into prices and the economy.
Before the bank’s last decision, there was a growing demand for the rate to be raised, as inflation had increased pressure on distressed households; in July, three policymakers called for the rate to be raised to 0.5%.
Inflation fell to 2.6% last month, compared to 2.9% in June, although the bank said it was expected to rise again in the coming months.
The bank said the excess growth over the 2 percent target was due to a completely weak pound.
Andrew Montlake, Head of Mortgage Brokers at Coreco, said: “In light of the recent decline in exchange rates, it seems the mortgage market is once again becoming increasingly competitive as lenders crave work and hope to finish the year in a positive way.
The stock exchange seems particularly favorable to those whose valid trades are nearing completion, as refinancing, often free of charge and at a low rate, has become increasingly popular.”
The NHS is preparing to prescribe a controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people.
Patients will have access to “transformative” HIV-preventive treatment from September after a battle in the Supreme Court over whether the drug should be funded by the NHS.
NHS England announced that National Health Service will now make available to an estimated 10,000 people a pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) tablet during the initial three-year clinical trial, which has shown an approximate 86% reduction in the risk of infection in people at high risk.
The NHS agreed to fund the clinical trial after the Court of Appeal upheld last year's Supreme Court ruling that the NHS was able to pay for PrEP, despite the agency's own claims that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
NHS England CEO Simon Stevens hailed the move as a "new large-scale intervention", while the National AIDS Fund (NAT) described it as a "revolutionary moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield are among the first to start enrolling people. In October, more clinics will be added before the program is deployed everywhere in England by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV drugs taken before intercourse to reduce the risk of contracting HIV.
Clinical trial results show that PrEP significantly reduces the transmission of HIV among people at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before intercourse means that there is a sufficient amount of certain drugs in the human body that prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken every day, or no later than two hours before intercourse.
Candidates for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people whose partners are infected with HIV and are not receiving treatment.
Clinics will identify eligible people who are willing to participate in a clinical trial, including men, women, transgender people, and those whose HIV-infected partner is not receiving antiretroviral therapy.
People who live in England and have chosen a GP there can also register their wish to participate at a local sexual health clinic participating in the programme.
The programme will cost <0xC2><0xA3>10 million and NHS England signed a contract to receive the medicines this week following an international procurement procedure.
The aim of the clinical trial is to assess the true potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on who the drug is intended for and how it is consumed and applied in the big picture.
Stevens said: "This new large-scale intervention should complement and amplify the comprehensive and increasingly successful fight against the spread of HIV.
“This is another milestone in more than three decades of fighting one of humanity’s greatest health challenges.”
Deborah Gold, executive director of the NAT, said: “This is a pivotal moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, if properly targeted to those who need it and are at risk, offers an opportunity to change the HIV epidemic in England.
Starting in September, people at high risk of HIV in England will have access to a powerful new tool, individually manageable and independent of negotiations with a partner, through this NHS-funded clinical trial, thereby improving many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement."
Ian Green, CEO of the Terrence Higgins Foundation, said: “It is now a priority to make sure that the clinical trial across the country gets underway quickly and that no one at risk of HIV is left behind.
Now that the PrEP clinical trial drug has been procured, we are on track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of contracting HIV.
Sharon Hodgson, the shadow minister for public health, said: “The start of the PrEP clinical trial is very welcome and long overdue after months of delays and dragging the government’s feet.
The evidence shows the magnitude of the changes that this medicine can bring to the prevention of HIV and the cessation of the spread of this life-changing infection.
This clinical trial takes us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
It is now important that the clinical trial is rolled out as soon as possible across the country to protect people who are exposed to HIV and bring us one step closer to stopping the spread of HIV in society."
The price of electricity increased by 12% in Estonia, while it fell in Latvia and Lithuania.
In July, the difference in the exchange price of electricity for the next day between the price areas of Estonia and Latvia and Lithuania decreased to 1.94 euros, compared to 7.71 euros in June this year, Elering said.
The main reason for the price difference is the breakdown of the Lithuanian-Swedish connection.
The average exchange price of electricity in Estonia last month was 34.33 euros per megawatt-hour, and the price increased by 12% compared to June.
In Latvia and Lithuania, the price fell by five percent to 36.27 euros per megawatt-hour.
In Finland, the price was 34.17 euros and the system price of the Nord Pool power exchange was 26.37 euros per megawatt-hour.
Prices increased by 12% and 7%, respectively.
Electricity flowed between Estonia and Finland for 75 per cent of the previous month’s hours in the direction of Estonia and for 16 per cent of the hours from Estonia to Finland.
For the remaining 9% of the hours, there were no next day’s transactions between the two countries.
Electricity moved between Estonia and Latvia 99 per cent of the time from Estonia to Latvia and 73 per cent of the hours had all the transmission capacity in use.
According to the transactions that took place on the last trading day of July on the Nasdaq OMX market, the exchange price of electricity could be approximately 34 euros per megawatt-hour in August and 37 euros per megawatt-hour in September.
The price of carbon dioxide, which affects the production price of electricity, rose last month and transactions took place at the price of 5.04-5.47 euros per ton.
Living high up - a half-floor and clever design tips have turned this small Earls Court apartment into a spacious home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker and passionate real estate innovator, swapped her large Knightsbridge home for an Earls Court apartment in 2014.
It is located on the first floor of the Queen Anne Terrace, and the fact that Joanne has not packed her bags and resold the apartment is a tribute to the new design.
"Before that, I lived with my ex-partner in Knightsbridge on a much larger surface," Joanne said.
“I was looking for something that would be equivalent to the price I was offering.
I was shown this Earls Court apartment, and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with it and made an offer the same day.”
Since its first visit, this 93-square-meter apartment has undergone a complete renovation.
At first, it was an apartment with a single bedroom and a complex layout - to get to the bedroom, you had to walk through the kitchen. Joanne wanted to add storage space and a half-floor to take advantage of the high ceilings.
“I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
Those were my demands,” he said.
He hired Erfan Azadi from Duck & Shed, an architectural and design studio based in Notting Hill, to take advantage of the 3.8 m high ceilings and create a home that would not just be a development, but a place where Joanne could live.
The ceiling was not high enough to add two rooms on top of each other, so it was an architectural challenge to create a half-story where one could stand upright.
Erfan had to approach the matter creatively.
"The metal construction is quite complex," he explains.
“We had to rearrange the rooms so that they would sit on top of each other without having to bow down.
It wasn’t just about building a platform, we used a steel structure to make sure the height of both the upper and lower room was right.”
This arrangement allowed Erfan to create two full-height rooms one above the other, with plenty of dramatic elements.
From the half-floor you can see the glamorous living room below from the old-fashioned Retrouvius window with copper light.
Mirrored golden furniture, silver details and retro-scented Serge Mouille light accentuate the style of the room.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding theatricality, spaciousness and lightness.
Mirrors are added at both ends of the short corridor to make it feel longer.
In the kitchen, the rear wall with a mirror gives the impression of a window opening into another room.
At the entrance, the mirror cabinet provides storage space for all of Joanne's cutlery and glassware.
The possibility of closing the kitchen part when not in use adds a charm to the living room, creating an image of a more glamorous space.
Folding kitchens are nothing new.
What is unique about this kitchen, however, is the fact that it is a garage-type retractable door.
“There was a bit of a design problem,” Erfan explains the steel-reinforced veneered MDF door.
"It has a counterweight, which is why it glides very easily when pushed up."
Thanks to smart use of space and storage space, Joanne now has 16 extra square meters, an additional bedroom and a better apartment plan.
“After all, the floor space is what you sell — or what gives the property value,” says Erfan.
"A real estate agent enters a room in an outdated form and makes calculations based on the floor area."
Here they have been able to increase the floor space, using high-quality materials that add luxury to the room.
“Materials are what you touch, and they help create an emotional bond with your home,” says Erfan.
"You don't fall in love with an electrical cable in the wall.
It’s important, but it doesn’t make the heart speak.”
This shows that a good design and an increased area will help to make a rather ordinary apartment something amazing.
In fact, they may even create a desire not to leave, as happened with Joanne.
The main character, Dane Jensen, is a bounty hunter in a Chicago skyscraper competing with a colleague for a promotion.
All that matters is the amount of money you earn, and you forget all about ethics.
He only sees his wife and three children early in the morning and late at night.
In the first half of the film, I catch myself thinking that this is the business version of House of Cards – even Kevin Spacey and Gerard Butler’s speech style is similar.
However, as the film progresses, the frame-like element becomes less and less, and the moralising intent of the filmmakers becomes more and more apparent.
A life-changing experience for the main character is his son getting cancer.
Now we have to make a choice between work and family life.
Aspiring to become an architect, his son makes his father walk to the big buildings in Chicago and think about the things that really matter: faith, goodness, love... not even the disaster of the Twin Towers.
After the third scene where the son opens his father’s eyes, the filmmakers feel that the goal is to make the audience cry, because even the most bitter-hearted viewer cannot hold back the tears from seeing the suffering of the beloved boy with cancer.
When his son falls into a coma and his situation seems almost hopeless, the father finally realizes the immorality of his work and does a good deed for the old man who is looking for a job.
Now I bet myself that if the film has a happy ending, I will reward my perceptiveness with coffee after the film, but if I’m wrong, I can praise the writer for at least one surprise.
For a moment, I suspect I'm missing a cup of coffee when my husband calls Dane from the hospital and he slowly rushes down the hall to his room.
The son, on the other hand, has miraculously recovered, and even though his father has just lost his job, it turns out to be a positive thing, because now is the time to deal with the family.
I can feel myself well - I can already predict the end of the American drama quite well!
To be honest, the film is well-constructed, all the necessary elements are there.
You can cry, you can laugh, the actors are good and the morals are beautiful: money is not the most important thing in life.
I think this movie will make a good comeback.
Trump’s new chief of staff plans to curb the president’s media consumption.
Others have tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can do it for real.
In that case, he would be the first.
The White House’s new chief of staff plans to restrict the flow of information, including news, to President Trump, in the hope that it will keep the chief of staff in the calmer waters.
Here's a snippet from reporter Josh Dawsey:
“When the new White House chief of staff, John F. Kelly, met with senior officials on his first day at the White House, he pointed out a key problem in President Donald Trump’s White House that he was planning to solve by getting bad information into the president’s hands.
Kelly told officials that information must flow through him, either on paper or at meetings, because the president would make better decisions if he was given good information.”
Kelly’s diagnosis seems perfectly logical, but others have also tried and have failed to tame Trump by monitoring his media consumption.
President Trump’s relationship with television goes back decades, and even now that he’s in the White House, his TV viewing habits haven’t gone away.
“When candidate Trump was upset by the dishonest media coverage, it was worth showing him that he was also fairly featured in influential publications,” former campaign adviser Sam Nunberg told Politico in February.
Politico Tara Palmeri wrote at the time that “according to six former campaign workers, the key to controlling Trump’s Twitter habits is to ensure that his personal media consumption also includes a steady stream of praise.”
Okay, okay, okay.
But the idea that Trump’s Twitter use habits have once been “under control” is ludicrous.
Maybe these campaign workers know something the rest of us don’t know, that Trump’s tweets would have been even more inflammatory without these interventions.
We’ll probably never know about tweets that Trump didn’t post.
If his assistants could save him from trouble even a few times, their efforts were worth it.
But no one has been able to stop Trump from consistently creating controversy.
Part of the problem is that in a White House of competing cliques, people are exclusively trying to promote their own interests by providing Trump with material that supports their worldviews, but may not always be reliable.
In May, Politico wrote about the advisers’ tendency to feed the president information of strategically questionable value.
One of the examples described by reporter Shane Goldmacher is as follows:
“Current and former Trump subordinates say Trump may react to negative press, particularly damaging information leaks, explosively, obsessed with identifying their source.
That’s what happened at the end of February, when someone gave the president a gleefully printed copy of an article on the GotNews.com website owned by internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson, accusing deputy chief of staff Katie Walsh of being a “multiple leaker” at the White House.
It doesn’t matter that Johnson has been permanently blocked from Twitter for taunting, or that he didn’t provide any concrete evidence, or that he’s made and withdrawn false accusations in the past.
"Trump read the article and started asking his subordinates about Walsh."
Goldmacher added that then Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and White House Chief of Staff Rob Porter “have attempted to establish a system for managing and documenting documents that reach Trump.”
How'd you do that?
Three months later, Kelly is trying to do exactly the same thing.
He may prove to be a more effective leader than Priebus, but Trump is still impulsive and his assistants are still competing for influence.
These immutable factors make Kelly's mission very difficult.
