Eesti Pank bought 149 million euros worth of bonds as part of the public sector asset purchase programme of the central banks of the euro area in July, while the central bank’s bond portfolio grew to 4.36 billion euros.
The central bank does not publish detailed information on purchases.
President of the Bank of Estonia Hardo Hansson has previously explained in reply to an interpellation of members of the Riigikogu that the asset purchase programme of the central banks of the Eurosystem includes three different purchase programmes: financial sector covered bonds (covered bonds), asset-backed bonds (ABS) and public sector bonds (PSPP).
The central bank buys bonds from the market in order to encourage investors who have sold bonds to invest money elsewhere.
Purchases have the effect of reducing the return on lower-risk assets and of motivating investors to take greater risks.
As a rule, within the framework of the public sector bond purchase programme, each central bank buys its own government bonds, while the bonds of other countries are not purchased.
As the Estonian state has not issued any bonds, Eesti Pank makes so-called replacement purchases within the limits of the volume allocated to them.
Substitution purchases are also made by central banks in those countries where the offer of bonds complying with the purchase programme is limited.
According to Hansson, Eesti Pank generally buys bonds from European institutions, such as the European Financial Stability Facility and the European Investment Bank.
Eesti Pank has been buying bonds under the asset purchase programme since March 2015.
In the meantime, Elering bonds were purchased, but Eesti Pank will no longer buy Elering bonds as of June 2016.
Starting from June, the Bank of Finland will buy Elering and Eesti Energia bonds on behalf of the central banks of the euro area.
Travelers Ignore Trench and Return to “Millionaire District”
Some of the wealthiest homeowners in the West Midlands have once again come into fierce conflict with determined travelers who have ignored a trench dug by the council to win back a field away from their villas.
Travelers have parked their 20 caravans in a field near Solihull Street, a wealthy “millionaire’s district.”
They have returned with an army of horses, children and trucks since they were kicked out in May, not to be disturbed by the trench dug by the council to prevent their invasion.
The tactical team found a weak spot at the perimeter, squeezing their vehicles through an unblocked section that had been left in the footpath.
Enraged residents have cursed Solihull’s council, saying the council is “useless in dealing with the problem.”
An anonymous resident said: "They moved there Monday night after being pushed out of Bentley Heath, where they threw stones at passersby.
The council needs to be shamed into taking action because they are useless in tackling the problem.
The travelers were there in May, they were chased away, and now they're back again.
"They came in last night, probably more today."
He added: “Birmingham Council knows how to deal with these issues by getting long-held seals to protect their parks.
I live on Streetsbrook Road and I’m not happy that I have to keep paying council tax when the council can’t even stop such a thing.”
One local resident, who also wished to remain anonymous, said: "This is ridiculous. We have just seen the last of these travellers leave, and there is already another offensive going on.
This time the number has increased, and the grassland has even seen a horse rummaging."
A representative of the Solihull council said: "We are aware that there is an illegal campground on the land near Streetsbrook Road, and we are cooperating with the Solihull police. We are taking the necessary legal measures to get them moving as quickly as possible.
