They are told that it is important to change your routine.
Two senior writers discuss which seems safer: either bringing the children to an office that was the target of a grenade attack in 2009 or leaving them at home.
Security experts have written three words on the board at the front of the room: "enemies", "neutrals", "allies".
They ask reporters to provide names in each column no proof is needed, impressions and gut feeling are enough.
Drug traffickers, politicians, businessmen, and journalists are suspected of being on government or cartel payrolls, along with a whole list of villains who make coverage of the chaos in Mexico dangerous.
