The dinosaur used a defensive color to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, although quite frightening.
Scientists have now revealed the first findings of an incredible rhinoceros creature discovered by a Canadian miner, which has been so well preserved that experts have described it as the "Mona Lisa of the Dinosaurs."
It is so well-preserved that it was even possible to identify that his scaly skin was a reddish-brown color and that his past was somewhat "difficult."
A report published in the journal Current Biology described the creature as "the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever found" and as "one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world."
The fossil is a new species of nodosaur that lived in the mid Cretaceous, 110-112 million years ago.
Its incredibly good preservation amazed researchers who describe it as “really remarkable.”
This armored vegetarian is the best preserved type of fossil ever found, according to National Geographic magazine.
It was discovered on March 21, 2011 by Shawn Funk while he was mining at the Suncor Millenium mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
He hit something that did not resemble the surrounding stone, and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
For the next six years, work was done to dig the animal out of a 2,500-pound (1,100-kilogram) piece of land.
After all this hard work, the end result is now finally ready to be released to the public.
"If you squint a little bit, you can almost believe he's asleep," said lead author Caleb Brown, a researcher at the Royal Tyrrell Museum where the creature is exhibited.
"It will go down in science history as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs."
Studying his skin, the researchers found that this herbivore, though covered in scales and resembling a walking tank, was likely at considerable risk from carnivorous dinosaurs.
This armored dinosaur used red and white armor to hide from predators, and employed a technique of concealment known as counter-shadowing, which is also used by many modern animals.
This allowed the dinosaur to better assimilate into its surroundings and avoid enemies, experts say, as larger dinosaurs likely hunted it.
This 110-million-year-old creature, part of the Nodosaurus family, first made the news in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Scientists have now studied the creature and named it after Mark Mitchell, a lab technician at the Borealopelta markmitchell Museum, who was part of a team that spent more than 7,000 hours in the process of painstakingly exposing the animal.
Thanks to the amazing preservation of the specimen, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the shape and size of scales on the animal’s body.
They discovered a counter-shadowing, a defense technique common in the animal kingdom, which means that the upper half of the creature was darker than the lower half.
Although the counter-shade is common, the findings come as a surprise, as Borealopelta is much larger than the animals living with the counter-shade today.
This suggests that the dinosaur was being hunted actively enough by other carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution preferred hiding as a survival tactic rather than confrontation.
However, most modern animals that use the counter-shade — such as deer, zebras, or armadillos — are much smaller and more vulnerable to prey, suggesting that the nodosaurus had to make a real effort to survive.
"The intense hunt for a huge and armored dinosaur shows just how dangerous dinosaurs from the Cretaceous period could have been," Brown said.
A chemical analysis of the armor’s organic compounds also revealed that the dinosaur’s skin was reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal for clues about its life, including the preserved contents of its gut, to find out what the animal ate for its last meal.
They believe that the dinosaur died when it fell into the river, thus reaching the sea with a current, where it sank backwards to the ocean floor.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as it is now in southern Florida, and the rivers and oceans probably extended much farther inland than they do now.
"This nodosaurus is truly remarkable because it is fully covered with preserved scaly skin, while remaining three-dimensional, retaining the animal's original shape," Brown said.
"As a result, the animal today looks almost the same as it did in the Cretaceous period.
You don’t have to use your imagination to reconstruct it – just squint your eyes and make it seem like you’re sleeping.”
The Cretaceous period was a time when huge, bipedal, carnivorous dinosaurs—theropods— roamed the Earth.
Although all of their king Tyrannosaurus rex lived millions of years later than Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been hunted by some of its fearsome predecessors.
These include the Acrocanthosaurus, a monster 38 feet (11.5 meters) tall and weighing six tons.
Scientists whose recent findings have been published in the journal Current Biology believe that Borealopelta was washed into the sea after death and mummified in the mud.
The creature was discovered on March 21, 2011 by Shawn Funk while he was mining at the Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and scales, and is intact from the muzzle to the hips.
These creatures averaged 18 feet (5 meters) long and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kg).
Two 20-inch spikes protruded from its shoulders.
Scientists believe that this armored herbivore made its way through what is now western Canada until a flooded river washed into its open sea.
But the dinosaur's undersea burial site helped preserve its scales in exquisite detail.
The petrified remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that lumpy armor plates along the dinosaur skulls still cover the remains of the skin.
As Michael Greshko wrote in National Geographic magazine, "Such a degree of preservation is as rare as winning the lottery.
The more I look at it, the more incredible it seems.
The petrified skin remains still cover the lumpy plates on the animal’s skull.
The right foreleg lies next to him, and the five toes are stretched upward.
I can count the scales on his feet."
How did one activist find the answer to the question "Whose streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was in total shock.
Just a day after traveling to New York, this St. Louis resident, via Airbnb, was sitting on a bed in a rented room, browsing Facebook on his phone.
He stumbled upon a post from his former schoolmate.
It said, "The police just killed an 18-year-old boy and he's still lying on the street."
He was confused as to why no one else had posted this information on his feed, so he closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
Posts by a longtime <0x40>TheePharoah user had repeatedly been shared on his timeline.
A rapper from the St. Louis area broadcast live tweets about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old black man killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body lying on the street for four hours.
"It's crazy," Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new to him or his community.
He put his phone away, but later in the evening saw another tweet announcing that this time people were gathering on Canfield Drive.
They shared photos of a police tape and screaming people, and a man claiming to be Brown's father and holding a sign that said, "The Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!"
He watched a live stream of a policeman standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another cop cocked a gun, he said, and shouted, "I'm going to kill you all... animals."
Ferrell remembers how he caught himself thinking, “This is unusual.”
"It's not the kind of murder we're used to, which we might call typical."
I felt scared at that moment.
I was angry and crying.”
He booked a return flight and drove home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., he went to his father to pick up his six-year-old daughter and decided that they would go to Ferguson the next morning alone.
What happened with Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the central theme of the new documentary “Whose Streets?”, which premieres in theaters on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of strength and tenacity from the perspective of the people who live in this community and who filled the streets demanding answers.
When Ferrell and his daughter—who was wearing a flowery dress and wearing a matching crown—were driving toward Ferguson, they had another conversation about what they had been talking about several times before that morning—about the experiences and living conditions of black people.
“Do you remember when I taught you how a black community had to fight for its rights?” he recalls asking himself.
"We're driving to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that's not right."
"I couldn't not bring him," Ferrell said later.
“What is happening now is the culmination of what has happened in the past.
You have to see it, see it, and grow in the middle of it.
She needs to learn about activism and organization, but also about the different layers of black experiences and living conditions, and what we need to do to become free and free ourselves.
Even if I manage to raise her without personally experiencing blatant racism, she is no different from any other black girl.
I feel like I would be doing him a disservice if I protected him from this world.”
The first stop they made when they arrived in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a place across the street from a police station that had become a sort of campground where activists waited for news of policeman Darren Wilson, who was never charged.
There Ferrell and his daughter joined forces with a local business owner who prepared lunches.
They put food bags together and helped distribute them to the protesters.
For Ferrell, a new type of activism slowly took shape.
"My activism completely changed after August 9," he said, noting that when he was a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, he was president of the Minority Nursing Students Association and focused on food justice and health inequalities in black communities.
“I didn’t have any organizational experience.
It all just worked out.”
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, the co-director of one of the films, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said he and film operator Lucas Alvarado-Farrar simply wanted to document what was going on.
The question that came to Ferrell’s mind was, “Are you trying to document what’s going on, or are you trying to find a story that can be exploited?”
Such skepticism was due to the countless cases of people — often white — coming into the community and trying to take advantage of its pain and resilience.
Folayan explained in a recent interview: “We had heard that the voices of people born and raised in Ferguson are not being heard, and we wanted to do it differently.”
Folayan had already struck hands with co-director Damon Davis, a regional artist known for his activism regarding death row inmates.
His involvement made the project appealing to Ferrell and six other locals who had been watched by the film’s “Whose Streets?” team for years after Brown’s shooting.
"In this documentary, no one speaks for us or for us, we speak for ourselves," Davis said.
“What was important to me was the way these people are portrayed, because that’s how I’m portrayed.”
While the goal wasn’t to focus on Ferrell’s experience—to show that the movement wasn’t about “redemptive guidance, but community gathering,” as Folayan said—he became the most open-minded actor in the film.
As a result, Whos Streets documents surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell’s life, such as falling in love and marrying his wife.
"I felt like I was naked," Ferrell said, laughing at the first time he saw the finished work.
“But I realized that doing this work and humanizing black people must be accompanied by a certain vulnerability.”
What’s more, Ferrell’s story highlights and refocuses the role of a black homosexual woman in the wider Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three initiators of the movement, who coined the hashtag #BlackLivesMatter after the murder of black teenage Trayvon Martin in 2012, are homosexual.
“Black homosexual women in leading roles have kept the movement going in general,” Ferrell said, “and that’s because we have to constantly fight on many fronts.
Black gay women have to carry all that burden."
Folayan agreed, noting that “the movement is indeed being kept alive by black women, and many of them are black homosexual women.”
He argues, however, that "it's not some kind of equal opportunity thing" - Ferrell was not chosen to be the centerpiece of the film because of his identity.
"He was a person who radiated the right energy," she said.
"But it's no coincidence that she was right on the front line, because there's a lot at stake as a black homosexual woman living at these crossroads.
You can see his energy through the screen.”
Meanwhile, news cameras from Ferguson have long since disappeared, but racial ties between the community and the police are still fragile.
Ferrell has been given a suspended sentence of 2.5 years for blocking the road.
He describes the socio-political climate in the area he calls home as simply “a bustle of thrashing.”
Nevertheless, he still considers important the mantra he has etched in his memory since he took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We need to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains.”
