Startups to help your business avoid becoming the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure employee satisfaction in her e-commerce startup, but the polls were inconclusive.
The answers were often vague, useless, or, even worse, misleading.
And even though he promised to ensure anonymity, some employees did not trust the process.
“This system was simply not consistent and objective,” said Errett, who runs Madison Reed, an e-commerce company that sells hair care products in San Francisco with 75 employees.
So he called on outsiders to help him.
New types of human resource start-ups are emerging to help companies find out what their employees are feeling.
By developing and licensing software that is specifically designed to measure employee engagement, they enable companies to conduct sudden surveys, target specific teams and demographic groups, offer employees anonymity and a hotline for complaints, and, in some cases, allow linguists to bypass C-level managers and turn directly to the board.
"Now there are tools like Strava and Fitbit designed to monitor health, but where is Fitbit for your business?" asked Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Redwood City startup Glint, whose software analytics tools are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
According to Erretti, in the three years she has been using Glint, she has gained a much better understanding of what her employees think and feel.
In addition to sudden surveys and surveys targeted at specific teams, it offers a company heat map that provides an overview of which departments have the most complaints and which managers have the lowest support, allowing them to identify the causes.
Companies have come to realize that they need to stay abreast of their working culture in order not to become the next Uber that has been embroiled in scandals since a former employee posted a blog post describing a harrowing environment that punished those who dared to speak out.
For startups like Glint, the desire to have an overview is a lucrative business opportunity.
The global area of management, regulation and compliance could be worth more than $118.7 billion by 2020, according to financial technology statistics website Let’s Talk Payments.
Convercent, a Denver-based Colorado-based start-up that helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, noted an increase in interest and activity against the backdrop of Uber’s dubious reputation this year.
Convercent has nearly 600 customers, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently signed up as a customer.
Like Glint, Convercent allows companies to send customized impulse surveys, collect confidential responses in real time, and view heat maps from problem areas.
It also provides an anonymous messaging line that allows employees to report inappropriate behaviour.
And when it comes to the CEO, complaints go directly to the board of directors.
“Public opinion has been hijacked by regulators,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of Convercenti.
Quinlan said that if a company is found to be mistreating its employees or behaving unethically, the company could face serious consequences, such as consumer boycotts, employee departures and lawsuits, even if regulators do not intervene.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees at 500 locations, has been using Convercent for more than a year to ensure that employees are aware of the rules and procedures and provide an easy way to interact with the corporate headquarters.
If the employee wanted to report the problem earlier, he had to find the phone number or email address of the corporate headquarters, file a formal complaint, and hope that it would be taken seriously.
This was often a daunting and uncomfortable process, said James Vitrano, general counsel for Ruby Tuesday, who said there was no good way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convercent, however, it is possible for problems such as discrimination, harassment, or unfair pay practices, which previously did not reach managers who operated in offices in other cities or states, to be identified and addressed more quickly.
“I’m able to get closer to a holistic 360-degree employee experience,” said Vitrano, who leads Ruby Tuesday’s risk management team.
"And we're protecting our shareholders from lawsuits against employees."
Quinlan said companies began to take ethical behavior, values, and employee engagement much more seriously in 2002, after the Arthur Andersen audit firm collapsed due to ethical violations in connection with the Enron scandal.
But it wasn’t until “social media became mature” that companies realized they couldn’t stop their dirty laundry from being publicly washed online.
"Before using technology to monitor ethical behavior, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging companies a periodic fee for the use of their products.
It’s a business model and an opportunity that has the approval of venture capital investors who have supported both startups.
In February, Convercent received $10 million in funding from Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, raising $47 million in raised capital.
Bessemer Venture Partners invested $10 million in Glint in November, raising the company’s total funding to $60 million.
Such investments come as no surprise when you consider the interrelationship between companies, culture and venture capital.
More and more research shows that today’s workers expect more from the workplace than ever before.
Competitive markets such as Silicon Valley have high salaries and interesting projects with mere stakes on the table.
Employees want to feel accepted and valued and that they are devoting their time to a company with a positive mission.
“When people are happy in a company, feel heard, and that the work they do is rewarding, they are more committed to ensuring the success of the company,” said Nina McQueen, vice president of the general benefit and employee experience department at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors earn revenue when the companies in their portfolios do well; companies do well when employees are engaged and engaged.
If third-party analytics tools promise to increase employee engagement and engagement, then it’s no wonder they find support.
Having data on employee involvement is important, according to the experts of the working culture.
But this data is useless unless the company’s supervisors do something about it.
In fact, when a company asks its employees for feedback, it can create expectations that change will come.
And if the changes don’t happen fast enough or not at all, it can lead to frustration and reduce employee engagement.
“If you’re asking for 4,000 proposals, you need to be prepared for 4,000 conversations,” said Russell Raath, president of consulting and business management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies make the mistake of relying too much on data collection.
“Because when things don’t get done, the employees think, ‘Did you really listen to me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why should I care?"
According to Erretti, Madison Reed, who now conducts monthly surveys among employees, has been able to implement the measures on the same day the problem has been reported through Glint.
And after receiving feedback from disappointed employees about the speed of decision-making and the quality of communication, he was able to reorganize several teams in the company and offer communication training to deal with problems.
However, Ruby Tuesdays is collecting new data on employees and it is hoped that in the long term this will lead to a longer-term commitment by employees in an industry known for its high workforce turnover.
