The rules for handling genetically modified crops must be clear
The Ministry of Rural Affairs sent the Bill on Amendments to the Release into Environment of Genetically Modified Organisms Act (GMOVS) and the Plant Protection Act.
With the amendment to the Act, the establishment of a separate database for the locations of genetically modified (GM) crops as well as for handlers will be waived, for which the plant health register will be used in the future.
In addition, the obligation of a GM crop operator to have a prior agreement with a person engaged in apiculture within the prescribed radius will be amended.
Although genetically modified crops are not grown in Estonia at the moment, we consider it necessary to have clear rules for the coexistence of genetically modified and non-genetically modified crops.
This is at least until a decision has been made to declare Estonia GMO-free," said Sigmar Suu, Head of the Plant Health Department at the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
"At the same time, it must be taken into account that the measures developed must be purposeful and proportionate, taking into account the costs and administrative burden for both the private and public sectors," Suu added.
The Bill repeals the provisions of the GMOVS related to the database of locations of GM crops and handlers and to the handling training, and establishes the requirements for the handling of GM crops and commencement of economic activities.
In the specific context of apiculture, the current obligation for GM crop growers to inform beekeepers of the start of GM crop cultivation is replaced by the obligation to reach an appropriate agreement with the beekeeper before the start of cultivation.
The Bill has been sent to the ministries for coordination.
All interested parties have the opportunity to examine it in the information system of draft legislation and, if they wish, submit their opinion to the Ministry of Rural Affairs.
The planned changes will primarily affect persons active in the field of crop production, beekeepers and the Agricultural Board.
In the European Union, including Estonia, only one GM crop is allowed to be grown – MON 810 maize.
So far, however, no Estonian farmer has been interested in growing GM crops.
This is due to the fact that there is no maize pest in Estonia, i.e. the European var. diet, to which maize line MON 810 is resistant.
Also, the varieties of this corn variety are bred for the southern regions, and this corn is not suitable for our climatic conditions.
The Ministry of Rural Affairs has commissioned studies in 2015 and 2016 to detect possible contamination with GM organisms in the seeds of different summer rape, maize and soy varieties grown in Estonia.
The results of the analysis of the samples taken showed that the seeds did not contain any foreign genes and as a result of the study it was concluded that the seeds of rape, maize and soy grown in Estonia do not contain genetically modified organisms.
From the above, it can be concluded that no genetically modified crops are deliberately grown in Estonia, and it was also confirmed that there has been no accidental contamination.
