The White House bill cost taxpayers thousands of dollars.
According to military documents disclosed to TIME magazine, the White House’s decision to fly a Navy helicopter last month cost taxpayers as much as $24,000 for an event celebrating American production in the southern courtyard.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Marine One during the President’s stay on board, was the central attraction of an event introducing American construction programs that took place at the White House on July 17.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and senior White House officials reviewed industrial products from all 50 states during their tour.
The helicopter, built in Connecticut, was exhibited along with a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a forklift truck made in Mississippi.
According to documents from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the White House War Cabinet required the helicopter’s presence on FARGO, a part of the order, just 36 hours before the helicopter landed in the southern courtyard for an “unusual” event.
"I wanted you to be aware of this because this is an unusually high-profile event," the HMX-1 commander said in an email to his commanding officer, a senior naval officer in the aviation industry, a day before the event.
The message stated that the helicopter would arrive in the southern yard at around 7 a.m. on July 17 for an event starting at 3 p.m. and would remain there until the yard was cleared between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m. on the same evening.
It added that if there were to be a delay in leaving the White House, a second crew would be needed for the return flight due to working-time restrictions.
The original flight crew was at the helicopter during the incident, and the squadron's security team remained close to the aircraft throughout its stay on the ground.
It was not possible to determine from the documents given to TIME magazine whether a second crew was eventually needed or not.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal workers from using government property for political purposes.
The documents show that HMX-1 investigated whether the event could violate this provision.
“We asked if it violated Hatch’s law, and we were told it wasn’t,” the commander wrote.
"You don't seem to have a choice," replied the deputy chief of staff.
The White House declared the event "made in America" an official event, and Hatch's law would not have covered it.
But even official events have political undertones.
The President supported the efforts of the health care reform discussed in the Senate at the time and praised efforts to keep government regulations under control.
The use of the aircraft known as ‘Marine One’ or ‘Air Force One’ for politically profitable purposes is not a new phenomenon.
