One drink of alcohol is equivalent to “training” the brain.
Livestrong writes that Dr. Gordon Shepherd is such a big fan of wine that he believes that wine can train the brain better than anything else in the world.
Shepherd is a neuroscientist at Yale University.
It’s not about alcohol or how it affects our feelings and thoughts, but rather about the “very active” process of tasting wine.
By smelling the glass, spinning the wine, enjoying it and sensing the aftertaste, we put our brains to work to create a taste for the wine.
According to Shepherd, wine molecules don’t actually contain taste, but the taste comes from the way the wine stimulates the brain.
He compares how the brain “sees” colors.
“The taste is not in the wine, the taste is created by the wine taster,” says Shepherd.
Things that still affect the taste of wine are, for example, our age, gender, and even the amount of saliva a person produces.
Shepherd, of course, admonishes that wine is not for getting drunk.
“There has to be more to it,” he says.
If you sip too much, the system is oversaturated.
Drinking too much wine can harm your brain rather than benefit it – according to a 2004 study, people who drink more than three glasses of wine are at risk of memory loss, loss of balance, and reduced mental capacity.
